Closing

The ISO 639-2 language codes have two codes B and T. According to [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_639-2), B is more of a legacy set based off of the English names, while the T set is based off on the native name. Additionally it says that T codes are generally favored. So based off of that, and the fact we are already using the T code for Chinese, this PR makes all of the langauges we have use T codes. This only required the changing of the German code, but will also need to be kept in mind when adding new languages in the future.

This is an extension of a suggestions made in #387.

The idea is that instead of just generating a README for this repository that has a formatted list of all of the OS Apps, a webpage on this project's Github Pages branch is created to display the apps. With the added flexibility of HTML, CSS, and Javascript, people will be able to interact with our content like never before. Filters, searches, expandable content, video demonstrations, better theming, you name it!

Obviously none of this will happen without work, so here is a very basic summary of what needs to be done:
- [x] Language flags
- [x] Theme switching (just swap the bootstrap stylesheets)
- [x] Improve tooltip display
- [x] Persistent settings
- [x] Screenshots
- [x] Parse markdown links
- [x] Fix internal links scrolling too far
- [x] Splash screen with loading bar
- [x] Fix links to users in "suggested by"
- [x] Background refresh
- [ ] Manual refresh
- [ ] Search
- [ ] Filtering
- [ ] Logo (see #413)
- [ ] Handle links in app descriptions
- [ ] Improve accessibility
- [ ] Sort order option
- [ ] Optimization
- [ ] Improve content (more tags, homepages, screenshots, etc. in the contents.json file)
- [ ] Filter out archived items
- [ ] Load projects for a particular `tag` (see #421)
- [ ] Screenshot thumbnails
- [ ] Refactor JS code
- [ ] Documentation
- [ ] Compress contents.json

If anyone with UX experience is reading this, we would love your help. I can help with the programming and content portions later this month.

It may be nice to have a way to include other languages in our repository. Of course people can just replace all of the English with another language if they want to translate, but it might be nice to set up a better standard for this so that multiple languages can be added, especially now that we are looking at more dynamic options (mobile app, webpage) that could allow the user to switch languages. Additionally, there some fields that are the same for all languages so duplicating the file for every language is a bit of a waste of space.

I would love to hear other people's thoughts on how this should be implemented. So far I am thinking that we should handle translations with a standard translation format (XLIFF, TS, or something like that), and then integrate an existing parsing library into our programs. The advantage of this is that it follows an existing standard and will be easier for people to translate since there are already graphical tools to help people translate with those formats. The disadvantage is that it is a completely different format than the main content. Alternatively we could add ids to all the items (something simple like lowercase title with dashes for spaces so we can completely automate that) and then there could be <language>.json files that follow the same structure as the main file, but only specify the id, and any fields that need to be overridden for translation. The advantage of this is the familiar format, and probably compactness. Examples:

Original

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

XLIFF (sorta)

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

JSON file (fr-CA.json)

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

> Is there a way of doing this by only adding "id" for the entries that are translated

Sure. In fact, the id can be implied for most cases. For example we could specify the id as a lowercase version of the title, with a dash instead of spaces. Then the only circumstances where you would actually need to specify is when the title is changed, or maybe if it contains special characters. The rest of the time, the programs can generate the id when needed from the title.

I think that having the readme generated is an excellent idea! It allows the end format to easily be changed and allows for easier reading by programs.

Here is my proposal for a JSON structure, using the v2ex app as an example:

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

There are two main types of objects here, the category object, which goes under categories, and the app object, which goes under apps. Here's the structure I was thinking of for each of them:

**Category object**
Required attributes: `title`, `id`
Optional attributes, with default value in parentheses: `description` (`""`)

**App object**
Required attributes: `title`, `category`, `description`, `source`
Optional attributes, with default value in parentheses: `lang` (`"eng"`), `homepage` (`null`), `itunes` (`null`), `stars` (`null`), `tags` (`[]`)
Notes:
- The tags attribute is for extra metadata for the app. For example a swift app would have `tags: ["swift"]`
- The lang attribute should be a [ISO 639-2 code](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_ISO_639-2_codes).

Let me know what you think, what you like and don't like. If you finalize a format, and it is easily parsable (JSON, XML, etc.), I will help convert the existing information to the new format. :smile:

_EDIT_: I just noticed that there are sometime subcategories such as Hacker News. For that I would suggest adding a `parent` attribute to the category object. Ex:

<S_CODE_TOKEN>
